# Leading loyalty programs share three design principles that the current program lacks
@type: comparison

@compare:
  header: Design Principle | Current Program | Leading Practice | Gap
  row: Value proposition | Transactional (points = discounts) | Emotional + experiential rewards | Fundamental redesign needed
  row: Tiering logic | Spend-only thresholds | Behavioral + spend signals | Rebuild required
  row: Personalization | Static email campaigns | Real-time, individual-level offers | Technology investment
  row: Partner ecosystem | None | 3–5 strategic partners adding value | New capability

@exhibit: Exhibit 2 — Loyalty Program Design Assessment
@source: McKinsey Loyalty Design Framework, 2024

@notes: The shift from transactional to experiential loyalty is not cosmetic. It requires rearchitecting the rewards catalog, the tier mechanics, and the technology stack.

---

# Redesigned program architecture creates value for the business and the member
@type: two_column

@col:
  ## What Members Get (New Model)
  - Personalized offers based on individual purchase history
  - Experiential rewards: early access, events, exclusive products
  - Partner benefits: travel, dining, entertainment integrations
  - Status that reflects total relationship value, not just spend

@col:
  ## What the Business Gets (New Model)
  - Behavioral data across all channels in a unified profile
  - Predictive churn signals enabling proactive retention
  - High-margin experiential rewards replacing low-margin discounts
  - Net Promoter Score lift from advocates, not just buyers

@notes: The key insight is that experiential rewards have a perceived value 2–3× higher than their cost to the business — dramatically improving loyalty economics.

